Dos funcion_citas inge :3 para facilitar las cosas :)

library(ggplot2)

den.plot <- function(data, var){
  ggplot(mundo) + geom_density(aes(mundo[,var], fill = "blue"), alpha = 0.4) +
    geom_density(data = data, aes(data[,var], fill = "red"), alpha = 0.4) +
    labs(title = paste0("Comparando la variable `",var,"`"), fill = "Estado",caption = "Rython | Luis Maron |") + xlab(" ")+ 
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "red"), labels = c("Sin Imputar", "Imputado"))
}#>>
den.plot.b <- function(data, var){
  plot(density(mundo[, var], na.rm = T),col="blue", main=paste0("Comparando la variable `",var,"`"))+
    lines(density(data[, var]),col="red")
}
den.plot.b(base1, "calories")#>>

getmode <- function(v) {
  uniqv <- unique(v)
  uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v, uniqv)))]
}
# datos[is.na(datos$sexo), "sexo"] <- getmode(datos$sexo)

Imputacion por la Media (Mean) metodo 2

from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from numpy import nan
from numpy import isnan

mundo = pd.read_csv("E:\\LuisxM\\Desktop\\IX semestre\\mundo para imputar datos.csv", sep = ";")
del mundo["country"] #

values = mundo.values
imputer = SimpleImputer(missing_values=nan, strategy='mean')
nuevo_values = imputer.fit_transform(values)
# isnan(nuevo_values).sum()
print('Perdidos: %d' % isnan(nuevo_values).sum())
## Perdidos: 0
newmundo = pd.DataFrame(nuevo_values, columns = mundo.columns)
plt.figure(figsize=(13, 9.6))
sns.distplot(mundo['calories'], hist = False, kde = True,
                 kde_kws = {'shade': True, 'linewidth': 3},
                    label = "Sin Imputado")
sns.distplot(newmundo['calories'], hist = False, kde = True,
                 kde_kws = {'shade': True, 'linewidth': 3},
                  label = "Imputado")
plt.legend(prop={'size': 13}, title = 'Estado')
plt.title('Comparando la variable: `calories`')
plt.show()
